Rutherfordium was named after Ernest Rutherford, a New Zealand-born British physicist and chemist who made significant contributions to the field of nuclear physics.

Meitnerium was originally going to be named after Lise Meitner, an Austrian-Swedish physicist who played a crucial role in the discovery of nuclear fission, but it is now known as Bohrium 107 in honor of Niels Bohr, a Danish physicist who made significant contributions to understanding atomic structure.

Lawrencium was named after Ernest Lawrence, an American physicist who invented the cyclotron particle accelerator.

Covingtonium was not actually accepted by IUPAC and instead Meitnerium is officially recognized as element 109.

Dubnium was named after the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research in Dubna, Russia where it was discovered, but it is sometimes associated with the Russian physicist Georgy Flyorov who worked at the institute.
